### *Exercise 8: UG Application Form*
html
<html>
<body>
  <h2>UG Application</h2>
  <form>
    Name: <input type="text" required><br>
    DOB: <input type="date" required><br>
    <button>Submit</button>
  </form>
</body>
</html>

*Explanation*: Simplified form with key fields.

---

### *Exercise 9: Shopping Cart*
html
<html>
<body>
  <h2>Shopping Cart</h2>
  <div>
    <p>Product 1 - $10 <button onclick="addToCart('Product 1', 10)">Add</button></p>
  </div>
  <div id="cart"></div>
  <script>
    function addToCart(name, price) {
      document.getElementById("cart").innerHTML += `${name} - $${price}<br>`;
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>

*Explanation*: Basic cart functionality with minimal JavaScript.

---

### *Exercise 10: ASP.NET Login Form*
html
<!-- Simulated HTML Login Form -->
<html>
<body>
  <h2>Login</h2>
  <form>
    Username: <input type="text"><br>
    Password: <input type="password"><br>
    <button>Login</button>
  </form>
</body>
</html>

*Explanation*: Basic HTML form (ASP.NET requires server-side code).

---

*Note*: These codes retain core concepts while being concise. For ASP.NET (Exercise 10), actual implementation requires Visual Studio and C#/VB.NET backend code.
